TY  - JOUR
AU  - Lustig, Hanno
AU  - Van Nieuwerburgh, Stijn
AU  - Verdelhan, Adrien
T1  - The Wealth-Consumption Ratio
PY  - 2013
Y1  - 2013/06/01
DO  - 10.1093/rapstu/rat002
JO  - The Review of Asset Pricing Studies
JA  - Rev Asset Pric Stud
VL  - 3
IS  - 1
SP  - 38
EP  - 94
SN  - 2045-9920
AB  - We derive new estimates of total wealth, the returns on total wealth, and the wealth effect on consumption. We estimate the prices of aggregate risk from bond yields and stock returns using a no-arbitrage model. Using these risk prices, we compute total wealth as the price of a claim to aggregate consumption. We find that U.S. households have a surprising amount of total wealth, most of it human wealth. This wealth is much less risky than stock market wealth. Events in long-term bond markets, not stock markets, drive most total wealth fluctuations. The wealth effect on consumption is small and varies over time with real interest rates. (JEL E21, G10, G12)
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rapstu/rat002
ER  - 



